What if fundamental analysis of stock prices was a temporary phenomenon? I =
have  previously written my half-joking history of stock markets in three e=
ras:
=09For hundreds of years, stock markets existed, you could buy and sell sto=
cks, but you had limited access to high-quality public financial informatio=
n, and no access at all to Microsoft Excel, so it was pretty hard to estima=
te a company=E2=80=99s future cash flows and discount them back to present =
value. Stock-market speculation was a psychological gambling game. =E2=80=
=9CThe actual, private object of the most skilled investment today,=E2=80=
=9D wrote Keynes, is=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cto outwit the crowd, and to pass the bad=
, or depreciating, half-crown to the other fellow.=E2=80=9D=09Then, startin=
g in about the late 1930s,=C2=A0a favorable set of conditions came together=
 for the rise of fundamental analysis. Public companies were required to pu=
blish audited financial statements, so you could analyze their cash flows. =
Books were written explaining how to do so. There were lots of fairly stabl=
e industrial companies, so you could predict their cash flows. Eventually, =
computer technology made it possible to do this more quickly and reliably. =
