   =20
 =20

The rough rule of US insider trading law is that it is illegal to trade sto=
ck when (1) you have material nonpublic information and (2) you have some o=
bligation to somebody not to use it to trade that stock. Most straightforwa=
rdly:
=09A company has fiduciary obligations to its shareholders, and isn=E2=80=
=99t supposed to trade in its own stock without disclosing all material inf=
ormation.=09A company=E2=80=99s employees have fiduciary obligations to the=
 company, and aren=E2=80=99t supposed to trade its stock when they have mat=
erial nonpublic information.=09A company=E2=80=99s various service provider=
s =E2=80=94=C2=A0bankers, lawyers, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0have confidentiality=
 obligations to the company and aren=E2=80=99t supposed to use inside infor=
mation to trade its stock.

There are more complicated cases:
=09The employees (and bankers, lawyers, etc.) of the=C2=A0acquirer in a pos=
sible merger have obligations to that acquirer, and are not supposed to use=
 inside information to trade the=C2=A0target=E2=80=99s=C2=A0stock.=09A roma=
ntic partner=C2=A0or golf buddy or former baseball teammate of a corporate =
employee=C2=A0(or banker, lawyer, etc.) has a duty of trust and confidence =
to the employee, and is not supposed to use inside information to trade her=
 company=E2=80=99s=C2=A0stock. (And a romantic partner=C2=A0of an employee=
=C2=A0of an=C2=A0acquirer=C2=A0is not supposed to use inside information to=
 trade the target=E2=80=99s stock.)

You need=C2=A0something, some duty to keep the information confidential. Fa=
mously,   in the US, if you overhear a banker talking about a deal on a tra=
in, you can go ahead and trade on that. (Not legal advice!) What makes the =
insider trading illegal is the breach of a duty, not=C2=A0just=C2=A0the ins=
ide information.
The US Securities and Exchange Commission does keep trying to expand the bo=
undaries, though. We have   talked a few   times about its =E2=80=9Cshadow =
trading=E2=80=9D case, in which it argues that an employee of a company is =
not allowed to use inside information about that company to trade in=C2=A0o=
ther=C2=A0companies with correlated stocks. The SEC sued an employee of a b=
iotech company that was a merger target who traded in a competitor=E2=80=99=
s stock, which went up when the merger was announced. The theory is that th=
e employee had a duty to his company not to use that inside information to =
trade=C2=A0any=C2=A0stock, not just his own company=E2=80=99s stock.
Or here=E2=80=99s one from last week:

The Securities and Exchange Commission [Tuesday] announced insider trading =
