<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What if fundamental analysis of stock prices w=
as a temporary phenomenon? I have <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbus=
iness.com/click/34887393.257355/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9=
uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDgtMjIvbWVtZS1zdG9jay12YWNhdGlvbi1pcy1vdmVyP2NtcGlkPU=
JCRDA0MDEyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0d=
GVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDQwMSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cBa46b7a5e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;"> previously written</a> my half-joking history of=
 stock markets in three eras:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">For hundreds of years, stock markets =
existed, you could buy and sell stocks, but you had limited access to high-=
quality public financial information, and no access at all to Microsoft Exc=
el, so it was pretty hard to estimate a company=E2=80=99s future cash flows=
 and discount them back to present value. Stock-market speculation was a ps=
ychological gambling game. =E2=80=9CThe actual, private object of the most =
skilled investment today,=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbu=
siness.com/click/34887393.257355/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubWFyeGlzdHMub3JnL3JlZmVyZW=
5jZS9zdWJqZWN0L2Vjb25vbWljcy9rZXluZXMvZ2VuZXJhbC10aGVvcnkvY2gxMi5odG0/607f0=
7ceef4b8524a319a23cB10be7f68" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope=
" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">wrote Keynes</a>, is=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cto=
 outwit the crowd, and to pass the bad, or depreciating, half-crown to the =
other fellow.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Then, start=
ing in about the late 1930s,=C2=A0a favorable set of conditions came togeth=
er for the rise of fundamental analysis. Public companies were required to =
publish audited financial statements, so you could analyze their cash flows=
. Books were written explaining how to do so. There were lots of fairly sta=
ble industrial companies, so you could predict their cash flows. Eventually=
, computer technology made it possible to do this more quickly and reliably=
. Mutual funds grew up with professional investors who did this analysis. L=
ater, the development of leveraged buyout technology made it possible for y=
ou to <em>realize=C2=A0</em>the value of a company=E2=80=99s cash flows: If=
 your fundamental analysis of a company said that it was worth more than it=
s stock price, you could buy all the stock and take the cash flows for your=
self. The result is that it was possible to <em>do </em>fundamental analysi=
s, and there was a clear plausible=C2=A0<em>link=C2=A0</em>between that fun=
damental analysis and the value of the stock.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bo=
ttom: 5px;">But eventually =E2=80=94=C2=A0like, three years ago? =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0people realized that there was a flaw in that reasoning. While the va=
lue of a company=E2=80=99s cash flows probably=C2=A0<em>does=C2=A0</em>set =
a real floor under its stock price =E2=80=94=C2=A0if the stock is worth les=
s than the cash flows, someone can buy the company and take the cash flows =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/348=
87393.257355/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMj=
ItMTAtMTgvbWF0dC1sZXZpbmUtcy1tb25leS1zdHVmZi1jcmVkaXQtc3Vpc3NlLXdhcy1hLXJld=
mVyc2UtbWVtZS1zdG9jaz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNDAxMjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVt=
YWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDA0MDEmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1=
vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB75e42702" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">it does not put a=
=C2=A0<em>ceiling=C2=A0</em>on the price</a>. If the stock has cash flows w=
orth $10, and you want to pay $20 for it, I can=E2=80=99t stop you, and I c=
annot directly monetize the difference: I can=E2=80=99t, like, sell all the=
 stock for $20 and then buy it back for $10; I can=E2=80=99t force the pric=
e down to the fundamental value. If everyone just collectively decides to p=
ay $20 for a thing with cash flows of $10, or $0, then it=E2=80=99s worth $=
20, isn=E2=80=99t it? There is no law of nature requiring that a stock=E2=
=80=99s price has to equal the present value of its future cash flows, or e=
ven that it has to equal the market=E2=80=99s collective=C2=A0<em>estimate=
=C2=A0</em>of its future cash flows. That=E2=80=99s just a matter of tradit=
ion, and the tradition is only like 80 years old. But the tradition could a=
lways change. Now maybe stocks will trade based on =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I don=E2=
=80=99t know, something else, collective attention, online sentiment, the d=
esire to =E2=80=9Coutwit the crowd.=E2=80=9D Stocks can once again be pure =
tokens in a psychological gambling game.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I said=C2=A0that the third era started =E2=80=
=9Clike three years ago,=E2=80=9D because that=E2=80=99s when GameStop Corp=
.=E2=80=99s stock <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/=
34887393.257355/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzI=
wMjEtMDEtMjUvdGhlLWdhbWUtbmV2ZXItc3RvcHM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDQwMTI0X01PTkVZU1RVRk=
YmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwNDAxJ=
nV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB00bd9871" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
  went to the moon</a>=C2=A0and inaugurated the era of meme stocks, stocks =
that trade=C2=A0purely on sentiment and attention rather than anyone=E2=80=
=99s views about fundamental value. But really I think the third era starte=
d a bit earlier, with cryptocurrency. I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/34887393.257355/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9mZ=
WF0dXJlcy8yMDIyLXRoZS1jcnlwdG8tc3RvcnkvP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA0MDEyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZG=
JnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDQwMSZ=
1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZiNhLXN0b3JlLW9mLXZhbHVl/607f07ceef4b8524a319a=
23cB505a71fd" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bla=
nk" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;">  once wrote</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Before the rise of Bitcoin, the conventional t=
hing to say about a share of stock was that its price represented the marke=
t=E2=80=99s expectation of the present value of the future cash flows of th=
e business. But Bitcoin has no cash flows; its price represents what people=
 are willing to pay for it. Still, it has a high and fluctuating market pri=
ce; people have gotten rich buying Bitcoin. So people copied that model, an=
d the creation of and speculation on pure, abstract, scarce electronic toke=
ns became a big business.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A share of stock is a scarce electronic token.=
 It=E2=80=99s also something else! A claim on cash flows or whatever. But o=
ne thing that it is is an electronic token that=E2=80=99s in more or less l=
imited supply. If you and your friends online want to make jokes and invest=
 based on those jokes, then, depending on your sense of humor and which onl=
ine chat group you=E2=80=99re in, you might buy either Dogecoin or GameStop=
 Corp. stock, and for your purposes those things are not <em>that </em>diff=
erent.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t know, I don=E2=80=99t entirely=
 mean any of this? A week into the GameStop thing in 2021, <a href=3D"https=
://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34887393.257355/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYm=
xvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDItMDEvZ2FtZXN0b3AtZ21lLWlzL=
W9sZC1uZXdzLWFmdGVyLXJlZGRpdC1kaXNjb3ZlcnMtc2lsdmVyLWZ1dHVyZXM_Y21waWQ9QkJE=
MDQwMTI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXI=
mdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwNDAxJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a=
23cB8950911e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bla=
nk" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;">  I wrote</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t think, however many days we ar=
e into this nonsense, that GameStop is a particularly important story (thou=
gh of course it=E2=80=99s a fun one!), or that it points to any deep proble=
ms in the financial markets. There have been bubbles, and corners, and shor=
t squeezes, and pump-and-dumps before. It happens; stuff goes up and then i=
t goes down; prices are irrational for a while; financial capitalism surviv=
es.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But I tell you what, if we are still here in a=
 month I will <em>absolutely freak out</em>. Stock prices can get totally d=
isconnected from fundamental value for a while, it=E2=80=99s fine, we all h=
ave a good laugh. But if they stay that way forever, if everyone decides th=
at cash flows are irrelevant and that the important factor in any stock is =
how much fun it is to trade, then =E2=80=A6 what are we all doing here?</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We were still there in a month, and people kep=
t emailing me to be like =E2=80=9Care you freaking out yet,=E2=80=9D and I =
kind of was, though now GameStop is down about 86% from its highs of Januar=
y 2021. Meanwhile the market capitalization of <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34887393.257355/aHR0cHM6Ly9jb2lubWFya2V0Y2FwLm=
NvbS9jdXJyZW5jaWVzL2RvZ2Vjb2luLw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB698c49b4" itempro=
p=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
>Dogecoin</a> has been higher than $7 billion for about three years now.=C2=
=A0<em>Much=C2=A0</em>higher for much of that time, and about $30 billion t=
oday, but consistently above $7 billion. With no cash flows at all. People =
just like that dog.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">With time, I have become more comfortable with=
 the answer to =E2=80=9Cwhat are we all doing here?=E2=80=9D The answer is =
=E2=80=9Cnot fundamental analysis.=E2=80=9D Maybe it is =E2=80=9Chaving fun=
 online.=E2=80=9D Maybe it is =E2=80=9Cplaying a complex game of mass psych=
ology.=E2=80=9D Maybe it is =E2=80=9Cusing our investments as a form of sel=
f-expression, buying stocks and cryptocurrencies we identify with and feeli=
ng better about ourselves if they go up.=E2=80=9D The third era is new, and=
 we do not understand the mechanisms=C2=A0here as well as we understand dis=
counted cash flow analysis, but maybe there=C2=A0<em>are=C2=A0</em>mechanis=
ms to discover; maybe in 10 years there will be textbooks on Meme Stock Ana=
lysis.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And maybe there will be a first-year M.B.A. co=
urse in Meme Stock Analysis. And maybe it will have a final exam question =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0really a first-week pop quiz question =E2=80=94 like: =E2=80=
